-- Update Project Milakko with complete Tier 2 Discovery Form responses
UPDATE form_progress
SET responses = jsonb_build_array(
  'Honestly, I started Milakko because I''ve always felt that food isn''t just something we eat — it''s something sacred. I grew up seeing how in temples, homes, and festivals, every dish was made with emotion, not just ingredients. But somewhere, modern food lost that connection — it became about packaging and profit, not purity and feeling. I wanted to bring that emotion back. To show that spices can still hold stories, prayers, and memories — not just flavors. Cooking for me was never a job; it was a ritual. Milakko started from that feeling — that if something is made with the same honesty as it was in old kitchens and temple feasts, the world will taste the difference.',
  'The problem is two-fold: practical and emotional. Practically, the market lacks truly pure, provenance-driven spices and chef-ready liquid essences that deliver consistent, powerful flavor. Emotionally, people miss connection — the sense that food can be sacred, healing, and historical. Milakko answers both by restoring honest ingredients, rigorous craft, and recipes that actually bring back that lost feeling.',
  'Before Milakko, people were using spices that just added color or heat — not soul. Cooking felt mechanical, rushed, and disconnected from its roots. Chefs were chasing authenticity through complicated blends, and home cooks were settling for "good enough." After Milakko, everything changes. The kitchen smells alive again — like something sacred is happening. Our products give people confidence, depth, and emotion in every dish. They don''t just cook; they create experiences that feel rooted, pure, and powerful. Chefs find consistency without losing craft. Families rediscover old flavors in a modern way. What we really deliver is truth in taste — that moment when food feels whole again, and you realize it''s not just about spice, but about spirit.',
  'I''d keep the Vision alive. If I could only keep doing one thing, I''d keep creating spice blends that carry emotion — the kind that make people feel something ancient and pure every time they cook.',
  'I''d never compromise purity — not by using cheap ingredients, artificial colors, or shortcuts that kill the soul of food. Milakko was never meant to chase margins; it was meant to protect what''s sacred about cooking. Once emotion and honesty are lost in taste, no profit can bring them back.',
  'Who I imagine Milakko is For. The Chef — the one who lives to create something truly different. He already knows his craft, but he also knows that a dish is only as honest as its ingredients. He''s always searching for that missing depth — the kind of flavour that only pure, thoughtfully blended spices can give. That''s where Milakko completes his story. The Home Cook like a Mother — she doesn''t cook for fame or money; she cooks out of care. She wants every meal to be pure, full of life, and good for her family''s health. She knows the importance of real spices and herbs — she can smell quality before she sees it. Milakko is made for her hands, her emotions, her kitchen. The Global Restauranteur — someone who understands legacy. He runs a restaurant that stands for something — not just good food, but truth on a plate. He values purity, consistency, and the kind of natural aroma that carries heritage. Milakko speaks his language — the taste of tradition reimagined for the modern world.',
  'How anyone find Milakko? Milakko won''t be "advertised" — it will be discovered. We''ll create curiosity through stories, not sales. Our first visibility will come from collaboration with chefs and restaurants, where dishes crafted using Milakko are featured as heritage-inspired experiences. The goal isn''t to sell a spice jar — it''s to let people taste legacy. Through curated features in premium food magazines, culinary heritage blogs, global chef networks, people will read about how Milakko revives temple kitchens, forgotten blends, and manuscript-based recipes. Each story, vlog, or chef-led tasting becomes an invitation — not an ad. We''ll host Milakko Heritage Tables — small, intimate dining experiences co-created with reputed chefs — where food writers, restaurateurs, and cultural enthusiasts experience the product before it''s even sold. From there, word spreads organically through the global culinary community, not paid marketing. That''s how people will find Milakko — through taste, trust and storytelling that feels like discovery, not promotion.',
  'People are tired of fake spices. Everything looks beautiful on the shelf but smells like nothing — just chemicals and dust. Every few months, they switch brands, still chasing that one real taste they grew up with, but it''s never there. That''s exactly where Milakko comes in — quietly, with honesty. To bring back what food has lost — the aroma that feels alive, the flavour that heals, and the purity that reminds us what real cooking was always meant to be.',
  'Before choosing Milakko, most people have their doubts — and honestly, they''re fair. They''ve tried so many brands that promised purity but delivered only bright colors and no aroma. So the first worry is always — "Will this really taste different?" For chefs and restaurants, it goes even deeper. They wonder if Milakko can stay consistent in every batch, if the aroma will survive the heat of their kitchens, or if it''s just another "artisan story." For home cooks, the question is simpler but more emotional — "Can I finally trust a spice that''s truly pure for my family?" They''ve all been searching for something real — not luxury, not hype, just truth in taste. That''s why Milakko exists. Once they cook with it, the doubts fade. What stays is the feeling — that old, honest connection between food and heart.',
  'Not everyone will naturally align with Milakko — and that''s perfectly all right. We can usually sense it when someone views spices as just another commodity, or values price over purity. Milakko was never meant for those chasing volume; it''s for those who appreciate authenticity and depth in every grain. When the conversation moves away from sincerity and towards shortcuts, that''s when we know it may not be the right fit. We''d rather stay true to what we believe in — preserving the emotion, heritage, and honesty that belong to real taste.',
  '"I''ve travelled and tasted cuisines across continents — but this… this feels ancient, like something the world forgot." "It''s not just a spice; it''s a memory reawakened. The aroma doesn''t shout, it whispers truth." "Milakko reminded me that purity can have power — quiet, graceful power." "Every jar feels like it carries a story — you can sense devotion behind it, not marketing." If people across kitchens, homes, and restaurants feel that — that Milakko reconnects them to what food once meant, not just how it tasted — then we''ve done something the world hasn''t seen before.',
  'When people refer Milakko, I hope they say — "You should work with them because Milakko doesn''t just sell spices; it revives the soul of cooking. Every blend feels alive, carrying a forgotten story within it. They''re not chasing trends — they''re preserving traditions and transforming them into something timeless." People will recommend Milakko not for its products alone, but for what it represents — honesty, emotion, and a rare balance of purity and innovation. Working with Milakko feels like being part of a living legacy where food is treated as culture, not commerce.',
  'When an individual approaches Milakko, they do not merely come to purchase — they come to rediscover. They enter a space where the quiet rhythm of heritage still breathes, where every spice carries a lineage, and where ancient kitchens whisper their secrets once more. 1. The Welcome — A Return to Heritage. We receive each guest not as a transaction, but as a continuation of tradition. A gentle conversation begins — one where we listen, understand, and connect with their culinary spirit. Every dialogue with Milakko begins with respect for curiosity. 2. The Discovery — Unfolding the Ancient Table. We then guide them through our world — the origins, the pairings, and the forgotten philosophies behind our creations. Each blend, each nectar, and each duo is shared as one would share a family heirloom — with reverence and storytelling. 3. The Selection — A Personalised Offering. Once the essence of their taste is understood, we help them select what resonates — not just what pleases the palate, but what speaks to their memory of food as culture. Orders are then placed with ease and clarity, free from haste. 4. The Craft — Preparation with Honour. Every order is hand-prepared from our small-batch atelier. The spices are measured, sealed, and finished with grace — ensuring the aroma that leaves our workshop carries the same sanctity as when it was conceived. 5. The Delivery — A Gesture of Gratitude. The parcel that arrives at their door is more than a product — it is a message from Milakko''s heart. Within it lies a note of appreciation, a token of the sincerity that defines our every act. 6. The Continuation — Relationship Beyond the Order. Even after delivery, our connection endures. We listen, we learn, and we remain available — because for us, every patron becomes a custodian of this revival, a part of the living story that Milakko continues to write. At Milakko, the journey from hello to here it is is not a process — it is a ritual. It honours the grace of old kitchens, the purity of natural craft, and the timeless truth that food, when born of sincerity, becomes culture itself.',
  'At Milakko, we do not measure worth by speed nor success by convenience. We are the keepers of an old rhythm — a rhythm that honours patience, purity, and the quiet craftsmanship that modernity too often forgets. There are many things we could simplify, but we do not. 1. We source by legacy, not by logistics. Instead of purchasing bulk commodities, we trace every spice to its heritage soil — to the very farms and regions where its story first began. We spend weeks verifying authenticity, speaking to cultivators, and ensuring each harvest retains its rightful character. It costs more, it takes longer, but it gives truth to flavour. 2. We blend by hand, in small batches. Machines could mix faster — but they cannot respect aroma. Each Milakko blend is hand-measured and gently layered, so the oils within every spice breathe naturally. This labour is deliberate; it preserves the soul of the ingredient rather than stripping it away for efficiency. 3. We test for purity beyond regulation. Where most stop at compliance, we continue toward conscience. Our ingredients undergo extended purity and microbial checks, not out of necessity, but out of reverence. We owe that diligence to the ancient kitchens that never compromised their sanctity. 4. We tell the story behind every jar. Writing and designing each product''s story takes time — and yes, it adds cost. But to us, a spice without a story is an empty fragrance. Every label, every narrative is crafted to restore the sense of wonder that once surrounded food. 5. We package as heritage deserves. Our bottles, our textures, and our design language echo timeless grace. It would be easier to print, pack, and post. Instead, we seal each piece as one would a letter of lineage — something to be opened with emotion, not indifference.',
  'Shortcuts Others Take — And That Milakko Will Not. 1. Buying anonymity instead of provenance. Many procure spices from large commodity traders, valuing price and ease over origin. We refuse this. Each ingredient must carry a known lineage — the region, the farmer, the harvest — because provenance is the difference between a flavour and a memory. 2. Mass-mixing in favour of machine speed. Industry practice favours mechanised, large-scale blending to save time. We will not. Small-batch, hand-blended mixes preserve volatile oils and nuance; haste flattens character and robs spice of its voice. 3. Meeting regulation only, not conscience. It is common to stop at legal compliance. We go farther: extended purity checks, sensory verification, and ethical audits. Compliance is a floor; our conscience is the ceiling. 4. Packaging for cost, not for care. Many choose the cheapest pack that moves product. Milakko packages as a ritual — materials, sealing, and presentation protect aroma and tell the story. Cheapness diminishes both scent and sentiment. 5. Selling product without educating the patron. Commerce often ends at the sale. We begin a dialogue. Recipes, pairings, provenance notes and care guidance are not optional extras for us — they are part of the stewardship we owe to every customer and to the traditions we revive. 6. Using templated stories instead of lived narratives. Brand storytelling frequently leans on generic copy and hollow heritage claims. We will only publish stories we can substantiate — living narratives drawn from our growers, our blends, and the rites of the kitchen. These are not mere preferences; they are pledges. They cost time and demand greater care, yet they are precisely how Milakko honours a tradition that will not be hurried or sold cheaply.',
  'When We Choose to Say No. There will come a time — as there always does in business — when opportunity arrives dressed in compromise. At Milakko, that is where our conviction begins. We have, on more than one occasion, declined offers from prospective distributors who wished to alter our formulations for easier profit. They proposed we reduce concentration, use common fillers, or replace small-batch production with machine blending to scale faster. The numbers were attractive, but the intent was not. To have accepted would have meant betraying everything Milakko stands for — the sanctity of heritage, the purity of our ingredients, and the reverence for the ancient kitchen we seek to revive. And so, we said no. Calmly, courteously, but decisively. For us, the line is unmistakable: We shall never accept money that asks us to dilute authenticity, hasten craftsmanship, or decorate deception. We are building Milakko to be timeless, not merely successful. There is no profit great enough to purchase our principles. When one works with the spirit of legacy, every decision is a reflection upon those who came before us. And thus, when the choice lies between more and right, we shall always choose right — even if it costs us the sale.',
  'At Milakko, when an issue arises our instinct is immediate and principled: acknowledge with grace, investigate with care, and restore with honour. We treat each matter not as a mere transaction to be closed, but as an opportunity to protect the trust placed in our revival of the ancient kitchen. 1. Acknowledge promptly, with warmth. Even before the facts are fully known, we send a personal message to the customer thanking them for telling us, offering a sincere apology, and assuring them we are on the case. Silence is never our response. 2. Collect only what is necessary — courteously. We request the essential details (order number, brief description, photograph if helpful) phrased kindly so the customer feels supported rather than burdened. 3. Investigate deliberately, not hastily. Whilst fast, our inquiry is thoughtful: batch tracing, packaging review and a review of handling. We prioritise understanding the root rather than jumping to blame. 4. Propose a clear, fair remedy — and act quickly. On conclusion of the review we present straightforward options (replacement, refund, or suitable compensation) and execute the chosen remedy without fuss. If the fault is ours, we accept the cost and responsibility. 5. Record and repair the source. Every incident is logged in our atelier''s quality record. Findings lead to corrective steps — supplier dialogue, process refinement or staff guidance — so the matter is less likely to recur. 6. Follow up to restore confidence. After resolution we check in personally to ensure satisfaction. Restoring relationship matters as much as rectifying the error.',
  'A singular habit — rather quaint, occasionally trying, but absolute: every single small-batch release must pass our sensory tasting ritual. We convene as a small circle (no fewer than two and no more than five), taste the batch, note the aroma, mouthfeel and aftertaste, and each member signs the tasting ledger with a short note. No product ships without that assent. Why insist, even if it vexes the team? Because flavour is ephemeral and easily lost to convenience. This ritual: 1. Preserves nuance — volatile oils and subtle notes reveal themselves only to the patient palate. 2. Prevents drift — recipes remain faithful to their origin rather than slowly morphing under expediency. 3. Trains and aligns the team — it builds a shared language of quality and cultivates responsibility. 4. Honors our promise — it is a living proof that Milakko is a revival, not a factory. Yes, it adds time and the ledger collects a good many signatures. Yet we prefer a small delay to the quiet betrayal of taste. This habit will be in place from day one of our launch in two months — for the sake of integrity, and for the pleasure of those who will one day open our jars and remember what true flavour feels like.',
  'While surveying the modern spice market, the pattern was unmistakable: spices had become commodities — efficient, anonymous and stripped of context. Shelves groaned with identical jars, labels shouted discounts, and most blends read like recipes engineered for cost minimisation rather than memory. The very things that once made spice sacred — place, lineage, method — were missing from the conversation. Concurrently, I observed an emerging longing among discerning cooks and culture-minded consumers: a desire for authenticity, provenance, and narrative. People wanted more than heat or seasoning; they wanted a connection to a story, to a region, to a tradition they could trust and feel proud to share. Yet there was no brand that married rigorous provenance, small-batch craft and refined storytelling into a single, elegant offering. There was also a practical gap: large-scale supply chains prioritise speed and price, which dilutes aroma and nuance. Small growers with true heritage crops lacked access to a market that would value their labour and preserve their methods. The result was a disconnect — exceptional raw material existed, but the market treated it like any other ingredient. These observations revealed a clear opening: not merely another spice label, but a cultivated revival — a brand that restores the rituals of the ancient kitchen, invests in provenance, handcrafts blends, and presents them with the dignity they deserve. In short: while others fought over existing aisles, Milakko could create an entirely new shelf — one of heritage, education and sensory fidelity. That is where we will stand, and why there is room for us to make the competition largely irrelevant.',
  'When I first conceived Milakko, I recognised a quiet emptiness in the market — a space where heritage, purity, and emotion had been lost to uniformity. Most spice brands, whether mass or premium, compete on convenience, price, or surface-level "exotic" appeal. Yet no one truly honours the ancient kitchen as a cultural institution — the place where India''s timeless flavours, rituals, and healing wisdom were born. Today, a consumer may choose between the predictable reliability of Everest or MDH, the global polish of McCormick, or the boutique charm of small artisanal brands — but all operate the same "flavour products." Milakko crafting a new category — The Heritage Kitchen Revival. We treat each blend not as a commodity, but as an heirloom — traceable to its origin, prepared in small ritualistic batches, and presented with the dignity of history. In doing so, Milakko transforms an everyday act — cooking — into a sensory and cultural experience. That is the gap I saw: the absence of reverence. And that is the space Milakko fills — a refined, story-rich, and soul-rooted brand that makes competition largely irrelevant.',
  'When people speak of spices today, I often hear a quiet disappointment beneath their words. The most frequent lament is that everything tastes the same now — that what once carried warmth, aroma, and memory has been replaced by uniform blends stripped of life. Secondly, many complain that brands have forgotten the story — that spices are sold like mechanical commodities, with no whisper of where they came from, who grew them, or what rituals once surrounded their use. The emotional connection between the kitchen and the soil has been lost. And lastly, there is a growing fatigue around additives, fillers, and exaggerated claims. People want purity but receive packaging; they want authenticity but find marketing gloss. Milakko was born from these very frustrations. We restore integrity, trace origin, and revive the soul of the kitchen — where every jar carries a story, every blend has a lineage, and every aroma feels like home rediscovered.',
  'Milakko stands in the premium segment, distinctly above conventional mass-market spice brands and modestly above most boutique artisanal labels. Our pricing reflects not only the rarity of ingredients and the precision of small-batch craftsmanship, but also the heritage, storytelling, and cultural integrity that accompany every product. While typical household spice brands prioritise volume and affordability, Milakko values provenance and sensory fidelity. On average, our prices may sit 45% higher than established market leaders such as Everest or MDH, and 20% higher than niche artisanal competitors. This positioning is intentional — Milakko is not designed for mass convenience, but for those who appreciate authenticity, heritage, and refinement in their culinary experiences. Each jar is a collector''s piece of culture, not merely a packet of spice.',
  'Milakko is built to be perceived as a house of trust, heritage, and legacy — ancient in its soul, yet graceful in its modern expression. We do not aspire to appear merely big or boutique; we aspire to feel respected, timeless, and enduring. Every element — from our sourcing philosophy to our design language — is guided by reverence: reverence for tradition, for honest craftsmanship, and for the ancestral kitchens that shaped our civilisation''s taste. When people encounter Milakko, they should sense the quiet confidence of an old heritage institution — a brand that stands not on trend, but on trust, lineage, and respect.',
  'Dear [Customer''s Name], I trust this message finds you in fine spirits. Allow me to extend my heartfelt gratitude for choosing Milakko. Each creation from our house is a quiet tribute to time-honoured traditions — crafted with patience, respect, and an unwavering pursuit of purity. It gives me great joy to know that our work now finds a place in your kitchen. Should you have a moment, I would be delighted to hear how your experience has been thus far. Your reflections mean more to us than any accolade, for they guide us in our endeavour to preserve authenticity while shaping a new chapter in taste. With warm regards and deepest appreciation, Abhimanyu Bishnoi, Founder & Chief Executive, Milakko',
  'You know, I run a group called Kolum — it''s not just business for me, it''s more like preserving old India in a modern way. Everything I do is rooted in heritage and culture — whether it''s agriculture, spices, or fragrances. One of my favourite projects is Milakko. It''s about bringing back the real taste of food — that pure aroma you''d find in old temple kitchens, where cooking felt sacred. I want people to experience that again — the feeling that food isn''t just eaten, it''s felt. So yes, I''d say I work to revive traditions — just in a way the modern world can touch and taste.',
  '"Sacred. Cultured. Eternal." Why these are completely Milakko''s own: Sacred — Because Milakko doesn''t treat food as commerce; it treats it as a form of worship. Every aroma, every blend carries the sanctity of the old temples and kitchens where cooking was prayer. Cultured — Because Milakko embodies refinement — not luxury alone, but a civilisation''s grace. It''s a revival of Indian legacy, presented with the etiquette of global sophistication. Eternal — Because Milakko is not a trend; it''s a timeless inheritance. It belongs to the past, the present, and the future — untouched by fashion, guided by legacy.',
  'If Milakko were to be compared to another well-known business, I would be honoured if it were likened to Hermès — not because of luxury alone, but because Hermès represents craftsmanship guarded by time, devotion without haste, and heritage translated for the modern world. Much like Hermès, Milakko is not built for the impatient market, but for those who understand that true refinement breathes in patience, purity, and permanence. On the other hand, it would feel entirely misplaced to be compared to Nestlé or any large-scale FMCG conglomerate. While they stand for efficiency and reach, Milakko stands for intimacy and reverence — where each jar is a cultural heirloom, not a commodity. Milakko''s ambition is not to dominate the shelves; it is to elevate kitchens into sanctuaries of heritage and aroma. It''s not about category — it''s about ethos. Hermès doesn''t compete with fashion trends, just as Milakko doesn''t compete with other spice brands. "Both lives in a world of their own creation, untouched by ordinary competition."',
  'We are beginning entirely from scratch, with only the heritage-style bottle finalised — inspired by ancient temple vessels and apothecary glass. The visual identity should feel timeless, sacred, and cultured, echoing India''s ancestral kitchens and the ritualistic calm of heritage cooking. Logo direction: a refined serif wordmark with a subtle heritage motif or monogram "M" — simple, poised, and unmistakably classic. Colour palette: muted saffron, indigo, paper-sepia, and antique gold — warm, archival, and elegant. Materials: thick glass, uncoated handmade paper, deckled edges, restrained gold foil, blind emboss, and natural jute or muslin wraps. Avoid any synthetic gloss. Typography & patterns: dignified serif type, paired with a humanist sans for balance; hand-drawn spice and block-print inspired motifs used sparingly. Imagery: soft, natural light — like a temple kitchen at dawn — showing hands, spices, oils, and textures that feel human and real. Sanskrit Note: each jar will carry a visible Sanskrit verse — not decorative, but purposeful — invoking reverence and curiosity. It becomes Milakko''s spiritual signature. Intent: every visual choice is designed to separate Milakko from the commodity-driven spice market. We''re not packaging flavour; we''re reviving heritage and sanctity — turning every jar into an heirloom of culture.',
  'I''m instinctively drawn to natural, time-worn tones — colours that breathe authenticity rather than shout for attention. Shades like warm sepia, muted sand, aged parchment, soft antique gold, and raw linen speak to me. They feel honest, grounded, and enduring — much like the spirit of Milakko itself. I also have an affection for deep indigo and twilight blue, not the loud royal versions but the kind that evoke monsoon clouds or the ocean before dawn — mysterious, contemplative, and quietly luxurious. On the other hand, I tend to avoid overly bright, synthetic shades — neons, hard reds, or glossy chromes — anything that feels forced or commercial. Milakko belongs in a calmer spectrum, where emotion meets craft, and the visual tone invites curiosity rather than demands attention.',
  'Yes — there are several elements that quietly anchor Milakko''s visual and emotional world. The Mortar & Pestle — a timeless emblem of transformation. It represents patience, craft, and the intimate connection between human hands and raw nature — where every spice begins its journey. The Spice Route Map & Ancient Seal Marks — symbols of global exchange and discovery. They echo Milakko''s spirit: Indian at heart, yet worldly in imagination. Temple Bells & Sandstone Arches — drawn from heritage architecture, they reflect harmony, rhythm, and the idea that food, like devotion, can be sacred. Sanskrit Script Motifs — subtly woven into our packaging, these remind the beholder that language itself can be aroma — ancient, poetic, and mysterious. Landmark Inspiration: the desert wind of Rajasthan and the coastal calm of Malabar — the two ends of India''s spice soul. Together, they form the unseen geography of Milakko.'
)
WHERE engagement_id = (
  SELECT id FROM engagements 
  WHERE project_name ILIKE '%milak%' 
  ORDER BY created_at DESC 
  LIMIT 1
);
